ental property to seeing children as independent bearers of rights. In The Challenge of Children’s Rights for Canada, Canada’s obligations and the rights of children are examined from the perspectives of research and development in the fields of developmental psychology, developmental neuroscience, law and family policy. This timely and accessible book will be of interest to academics, policy-makers and anyone who cares about children and about taking children’s rights seriously.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild welfarexCanada. 0aChild welfarezCanada. 0aChildrenxGovernment policyxCanada. 0aChildrenxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aChildren's rightsxCanada. 0aChildren's rightszCanada. 0aEnfantsxDroitsxCanada. 0aEnfantsxDroitszCanada. 0aEnfantsxPolitique gouvernementalexCanada. 0aEnfantsxPolitique gouvernementalezCanada. 0aEnfantsxProtection, assistance, etcxCanada. 0aEnfantsxProtection, assistance, etc.zCanada. 0aJeunessexProtection, assistance, etcxCanadaxCanadaxCanada. 0aJeunessexProtection, assistance, etc.zCanadazCanadazCanada. 4aLaw: Child Advocacy. 4aPolitical Science: Social Policy. 4aPolitical Science: Social Services. 4aSocial Science: Social Work. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aHowe, R. Brian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920856840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208568423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208568/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0